	</form></div><span class="pb doctop" title="page number in print edition" id="ADMS-06-04-02-pb-0039">39<a style="padding-left: 5px" onclick="window.open('/img-document-get.xqy?image=ADMS/Pages/ADMS-06-04/ADMS-06-04-02-pb-0039.jpg', 'pageImage', 'scrollbars=1,resizable=1'); return false" onkeypress="this.onclick();" tabindex="0" title="Click to view image of page from print edition"><img src="/img-ML/page-icon.gif" width="18" height="20" style="vertical-align:middle;" alt="page icon"/></a></span><div id="PJA04d023" class="doc letter">

    <h1>From Isaac Smith Sr.</h1>
    
    <div class="docbody">
     <div class="opener">
      <table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">Mr. Adams</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">Salem Feby: the 29. 1776</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
     </div>
     <p>I wrote you One or two letters not knowing of your being coming home all that time.<a class="ptr" href="#PJA04d023n1" id="PJA04d023n1-ptr">1</a> We have nothing Material in this quarter.<a class="ptr" href="#PJA04d023n2" id="PJA04d023n2-ptr">2</a> By some people a few days since Out of Boston they seem to think they will move off soon, As the Transports seem to be in readiness to receive any thing On board, and that there are Apprizements on the Friends of goverments Estate but I apprehend itt differantly that is <span class="pb" title="page number in print edition" id="ADMS-06-04-02-pb-0040">[40<a style="padding-left: 0px" onclick="window.open('/img-document-get.xqy?image=ADMS/Pages/ADMS-06-04/ADMS-06-04-02-pb-0040.jpg', 'pageImage', 'scrollbars=1,resizable=1'); return false" onkeypress="this.onclick();" tabindex="0" title="Click to view image of page from print edition"><img src="/img-ML/page-icon.gif" width="18" height="20" style="vertical-align:middle;" alt="page icon"/></a>]</span>that in case of any Attack upon them they may have everything ready to imbark, and that incase of the distructions of Estates in a day of reckoning they may be Accounted for, but att present dont see any end can be Answerd by itt was such a thing ever to be put in Execution as itt would not put an end to the disputes. The Newbury Yankey Hero has taken Another White Haven Man.<a class="ptr" href="#PJA04d023n3" id="PJA04d023n3-ptr">3</a> By a paper of the 16 Novr. has some things in itt which we have not had before which suppose you will have from the General. Is there any probability of a trade being open to foreighn ports. The brig of Mr. Gearey fited Out by our Goverment has met with such an imbaresment as am of Opinion wont be Allowed to return there being a dificulty in the Customs which iff referd to Madrid which I suspect is the case<a class="ptr" href="#PJA04d023n4" id="PJA04d023n4-ptr">4</a> of course Our Minister will know of itt and put a stop to her coming itt being now more than three Months when Nothing else hinderd her.</p>
     <p>We have two ships stationd here and Marblehead, Manley and One or two believe will sail to day iff can get by.</p>
     <div class="closer">
      <p class="salute">Our family are well and your hum. servant,</p>
      <p class="signed">Isaac Smith</p>
     </div>
     <div class="postscript">
      <p>P.S. A few Nights Ago seven people belonging to One of the Above ships Tenders took the boat and got ashore att Manchester, there being but 10 more Aboad, she is gone up to Boston to get more hands.</p>
     </div>
    </div>
    <div class="docback">
     <div class="note-source" id="PJA04d023sn1">
      
   <p>
       <span class="docSource"><span class="dType"><abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ recipients copy (A recipients copy is assumed to be in the hand of the signer unless it is otherwise described.) ]">RC</abbr></span> (<span class="ref-terms">Adams Papers</span>).</span>
      </p>

     </div>
     <div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#PJA04d023n1-ptr" id="PJA04d023n1">1</a>
      
   <p>That is, he wrote to Philadelphia, not knowing <abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ John Adams (17351826) ]">JA</abbr> was in Massachusetts. See Smiths letters of <a href="default.xqy?keys=ADMS-print-04-01-02-0223" class="document">2</a> and <a href="default.xqy?keys=ADMS-print-04-01-02-0224" class="document">19 Jan.</a> in <span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ &lt;i&gt;Adams Family Correspondence&lt;/i&gt;, ed. L. H. Butterfield and others, Cambridge, 1963. ]"><span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Adams Family Correspondence</span></span>, 1:339, 342. The <span class="ref-terms" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ &lt;expan&gt;Other materials in the Adams Papers editorial office, Massachusetts Historical Society. These include photoduplicated documents (normally cited by the location of the originals), photographs, correspondence, and bibliographical and other aids compiled and accumulated by the editorial staff.&lt;/expan&gt; ]">Adams Papers Editorial Files</span> list 59 letters exchanged between the two men from 29 Feb. 1776 to 20 June 1786. Since Smith was <abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Abigail Adams (17441818), m. John Adams 1764 ]">AA</abbr>s uncle, his correspondence with <abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ John Adams (17351826) ]">JA</abbr> has been printed in Series II, but space limitations and the large volume of correspondence for 1776 resulted in 9 letters for that year being held out for possible inclusion in <span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ &lt;i&gt;Papers of John Adams&lt;/i&gt;, ed. Robert J. Taylor and others, Cambridge, 1977. ]">JA, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Papers</span></span>. These letters will appear in this and succeeding volumes of the <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Papers</span> when they meet the criteria for inclusion in Series III.</p>

     </div>
     <div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#PJA04d023n2-ptr" id="PJA04d023n2">2</a>
      
   <p>Terminal punctuation supplied.</p>

     </div>
     <div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#PJA04d023n3-ptr" id="PJA04d023n3">3</a>
      
   <p>The <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Yankee Hero</span>, a Newburyport privateer, took a two-hundred-ton brig bound from White Haven Harbor, Nova Scotia, to Boston with supplies for the army there (<span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Boston Gazette</span>, 4 March).</p>

     </div>
     <div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#PJA04d023n4-ptr" id="PJA04d023n4">4</a>
      
   <p>Probably Elbridge Gerrys ship the <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Rockingham</span>, which sailed in July 1775 for Spain under the auspices of Massachusetts to procure gunpowder, but which never returned to America. It was detained at St. Antonio, Spain (George Billias, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Elbridge Gerry</span>, N.Y., 1976, p. 125126). Smiths concern may have been provoked by an account from Cadiz, taken from a London newspaper and printed in the <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Boston Gazette</span> of 4 March, that two vessels carrying ammunition for America had been stopped at the request of the British consul. See also Smith to <abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ John Adams (17351826) ]">JA</abbr>, <a href="default.xqy?keys=ADMS-print-04-01-02-0237" class="document">27 March</a>, <span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ &lt;i&gt;Adams Family Correspondence&lt;/i&gt;, ed. L. H. Butterfield and others, Cambridge, 1963. ]"><span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Adams Family Correspondence</span></span>, 1:365.</p>

     </div>
